    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-04-14T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-04-14T23:00:00-05:00" n="282"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d282">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.945/1045: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Woods</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-04-15T13:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 15, 1924—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 15—6:54 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>69. My 68, April 14, 2 p.m.<note n="43" xml:id="d282fn43">Not printed.</note>
                    Although Japanese public in general and newspapers in particular apparently
                    expected the House of Representatives to pass the Johnson bill,<note n="44"
                        xml:id="d282fn44">The bin was passed by a vote of 323 yeas, 71 nays (<hi
                            rend="italic">Congressional Record</hi>, Apr. 12, 1924, p. 6257).</note>
                    and yesterday the press comments in that connection were surprisingly moderate,
                    this morning it is apparent that over night they have experienced a change of
                    feeling as a resentful tone has crept into newspaper articles which express
                    considerable apprehension over the status of the immigration question. The <hi
                        rend="italic">Jiji</hi>, not accustomed to speaking rashly on questions of
                    foreign relations, says: “No nation retaining the <pb facs="0469" n="375"
                        xml:id="pg_375"/> least trace of its self-respect could tolerate the
                    discrimination aimed at by the Johnson bill. The bill strikes at the very
                    foundation of American-Japanese friendship.” While the chauvinist <hi
                        rend="italic">Yorodzu</hi> says: “America is now taking advantage of the
                    weakness of the Japanese brought about by the earthquake and intends to insult
                    our nation.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Woods</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
